<methodology slug="go-project-structure">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>backend-systems</domain>
    <summary>Standard Go layout: cmd/, internal/, optional pkg/. DI via constructors, no globals. Graceful shutdown for servers.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>go</tag>
      <tag>project-structure</tag>
      <tag>layout</tag>
      <tag>golang-standards</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>structure</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
    <languages>
      <language>go</language>
    </languages>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Go Project Structure</title>

    <summary>Standard Go project layout using cmd/, internal/, and an optional pkg/ for code intended for external import. Applications live under cmd/&lt;name&gt;/main.go, private logic under internal/{handler,service,repository,model,config}. Dependency injection via constructors; no package-level globals. Graceful shutdown covers the HTTP server, DB pools, queue consumers, and long-running goroutines.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>The golang-standards/project-layout community convention is not officially endorsed by the Go team, but its cmd+internal separation is widely understood, maps cleanly to vertical slices, and prevents the two most common structural bugs: package-level global state and cyclic imports. pkg/ is routinely misused — it should contain code intended to be importable by other modules, which most services never need.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Bootstrapping a new Go service or CLI that follows community norms.</item>
        <item>Splitting a single-package main into internal/{handler,service,repository,model} once it crosses ~1k LoC.</item>
        <item>Adding a second binary (background worker, admin CLI) as a second cmd/&lt;name&gt;/main.go.</item>
        <item>Standardizing layout across many services so on-call engineers find files in the same place.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Tiny single-file scripts or quick experiments — main.go next to go.mod is enough.</item>
        <item>Library-only repos — cmd/, internal/, deployments/ are noise; structure by feature subpackages.</item>
        <item>Go modules being published publicly — heavy internal/ use prevents downstream consumers.</item>
        <item>Monorepos with many services sharing a root — prefer one Go module per service.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="directory-tree">
      <p>Directory tree, module init, cmd/api/main.go with graceful shutdown.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Default to cmd+internal. Add pkg/ only when you can name an external module that imports code from it. Add a second cmd/&lt;name&gt; only when a real second binary exists.</statement>
        <rationale>pkg/ is routinely misused as a dumping ground. Once code is in pkg/ it is technically importable; moving it to internal/ later is a breaking change for external consumers.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Standard cmd+internal layout">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[project/
├── cmd/
│   ├── api/
│   │   └── main.go        # HTTP server binary
│   └── worker/
│       └── main.go        # Background worker binary (add only if needed)
├── internal/
│   ├── config/
│   │   └── config.go
│   ├── database/
│   │   └── database.go
│   ├── handler/
│   │   ├── handler.go
│   │   └── user.go
│   ├── middleware/
│   │   ├── auth.go
│   │   └── logging.go
│   ├── model/
│   │   └── user.go
│   ├── repository/
│   │   └── user.go
│   └── service/
│       └── user.go
├── deployments/
│   ├── Dockerfile
│   └── kubernetes/
├── api/
│   └── openapi.yaml
├── scripts/
│   └── build.sh
├── go.mod
├── go.sum
└── Makefile]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="module-initialisation">
      <example type="good" title="Module initialisation">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[go mod init github.com/username/project
go get github.com/gin-gonic/gin@latest
go mod tidy
go mod verify]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="graceful-shutdown">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Graceful shutdown must close DB pools, drain queue consumers, and cancel contexts — not just call srv.Shutdown. Every long-running goroutine needs a select on quit or ctx.Done.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents stop at srv.Shutdown and leave background goroutines running. Under Kubernetes SIGTERM, this causes in-flight requests to be abandoned and queued messages to be reprocessed.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="main.go with graceful shutdown">
        <code lang="go"><![CDATA[func main() {
    cfg, err := config.Load()
    if err != nil { log.Fatalf("config: %v", err) }

    db, err := database.Connect(cfg.DatabaseURL)
    if err != nil { log.Fatalf("db: %v", err) }
    defer db.Close()

    h := handler.New(service.NewUserService(repository.NewUserRepository(db)))

    srv := &http.Server{
        Addr:              ":" + cfg.Port,
        Handler:           h.Routes(),
        ReadHeaderTimeout: 5 * time.Second,
        WriteTimeout:      15 * time.Second,
        IdleTimeout:       60 * time.Second,
    }

    go func() {
        if err := srv.ListenAndServe(); err != http.ErrServerClosed {
            log.Fatalf("server: %v", err)
        }
    }()

    quit := make(chan os.Signal, 1)
    signal.Notify(quit, syscall.SIGINT, syscall.SIGTERM)
    <-quit

    ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 30*time.Second)
    defer cancel()
    _ = srv.Shutdown(ctx)
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="config-pattern">
      <p>Constructor injection, interface-at-consumer pattern, typed config, and DI wiring for the internal/ layer.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use a typed config loader (envconfig, koanf, viper) rather than hand-rolled getEnv helpers. Hand-rolled helpers silently return defaults on type-parse failures.</statement>
        <rationale>A getEnv that returns "" on missing PORT instead of an error lets the server start on the wrong port silently. Typed loaders fail loudly at startup.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Typed config with envconfig">
        <code lang="go"><![CDATA[// internal/config/config.go
type Config struct {
    Port        string `envconfig:"PORT" default:"8080"`
    Environment string `envconfig:"ENVIRONMENT" default:"development"`
    DatabaseURL string `envconfig:"DATABASE_URL" required:"true"`
    JWTSecret   string `envconfig:"JWT_SECRET" required:"true"`
}

func Load() (*Config, error) {
    var cfg Config
    return &cfg, envconfig.Process("", &cfg)
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="repository-interface-consumer">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define interfaces at the consumer (the service), not the producer (the repository). The service file owns UserRepository interface; the repository package provides the concrete impl.</statement>
        <rationale>This is idiomatic Go: the interface lives with the code that uses it, not the code that satisfies it. It avoids forcing all consumers to import the repository package just to get an interface.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Interface at consumer (service package)">
        <code lang="go"><![CDATA[// internal/service/user.go — interface lives here
type UserRepository interface {
    FindByID(ctx context.Context, id string) (*model.User, error)
    Create(ctx context.Context, user *model.User) error
}

type UserService struct{ repo UserRepository }

func NewUserService(repo UserRepository) *UserService {
    return &UserService{repo: repo}
}]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Defining the interface in the repository package and importing it in the service.</description>
        <reason>Inverts the dependency — service must import repository. Idiomatic Go reverses this.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="package-level-global-state">
      <antipattern>
        <description>var DB *sql.DB at package level, accessed directly from handlers.</description>
        <reason>Global state is untestable (cannot inject a mock), causes data races when reset between tests, and makes the dependency graph invisible.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="pkg-misuse">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Creating a pkg/ directory for internal helpers, business logic, or service code that no external module imports.</description>
        <reason>pkg/ signals public API. Once there, consumers depend on it. Renaming to internal/ is a breaking change. Reject pkg/ without a named external consumer.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="cyclic-imports">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Package A imports B, package B imports A — produces compile error: import cycle not allowed.</description>
        <reason>Cyclic imports reveal a design flaw: shared logic should move to a third package that neither A nor B owns.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <example type="good" title="Breaking cyclic imports">
        <code lang="go"><![CDATA[// BAD: handler imports service, service imports handler (for error types)
// GOOD: define error types in internal/apperror, import from both]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="worker-goroutine-shutdown">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every long-running goroutine (queue consumer, ticker, watcher) must select on a quit channel or context cancellation. srv.Shutdown alone does not stop background goroutines.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents generate worker loops without exit conditions. Under SIGTERM, srv.Shutdown returns immediately but the goroutine leaks, processing messages against a closed DB pool.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Worker with context cancellation">
        <code lang="go"><![CDATA[func runWorker(ctx context.Context, queue Queue) {
    for {
        select {
        case &lt;-ctx.Done():
            return
        case msg := &lt;-queue.Messages():
            process(msg)
        }
    }
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="dockerfile-safety">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Dockerfile must include USER nobody:nobody and use a distroless or minimal base image for the runtime stage. Never run Go binaries as root in production containers.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents emit Dockerfiles without USER directives, leaving the binary running as root — a container escape vulnerability.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>The agent should (1) inspect the repo: is this a single binary, multi-binary, library? (2) propose layout: flat for small, cmd+internal for services, cmd+internal+pkg only when external import is needed; (3) generate the directory tree with empty .gitkeep placeholders + a working cmd/&lt;name&gt;/main.go + internal/config/config.go + a Makefile + Dockerfile; (4) wire CI (golangci-lint, go test -race ./...); (5) generate one vertical slice through handler→service→repository so the layout is exercised end-to-end. Do not let the agent introduce pkg/ unless it can name an external consumer.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Generate an end-to-end vertical slice for at least one resource to prove the layout works. The slice should span cmd/&lt;name&gt;/main.go → internal/handler → internal/service → internal/repository → internal/model with tests at each layer.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents generate empty directories and skip the actual implementation. A working CRUD endpoint proves package boundaries are correct.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Best practices for Go project structure:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Default to one binary, one module. Add a second cmd/&lt;name&gt; only when a real second entrypoint exists.</item>
        <item>Keep internal/ rich and pkg/ empty until proven otherwise; renaming pkg/foo → internal/foo later is painful.</item>
        <item>Inject dependencies through constructors (NewXService(deps...)); never package-level globals.</item>
        <item>Define interfaces at the consumer (the service) not the producer (the repository) — Go style.</item>
        <item>Set explicit http.Server timeouts (ReadHeaderTimeout, WriteTimeout, IdleTimeout) in cmd/api/main.go.</item>
        <item>Graceful shutdown must close DB pools, drain queues, cancel contexts — not just srv.Shutdown.</item>
        <item>Use a typed config loader (envconfig/koanf); roll-your-own getEnv invites silent type bugs.</item>
        <item>CI matrix on the two latest Go minor versions; go vet, staticcheck, go test -race -shuffle=on are the minimum gates.</item>
        <item>Pin tools used by the build via tools.go and go mod tidy for reproducible local toolchains.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>Common mistakes LLMs make when generating Go project layouts:</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs reflexively create a pkg/ directory and put helpers there.</description>
        <reason>This leaks internals once anyone imports the module. Reject pkg/ without a named external consumer.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generated cmd/api/main.go often skips defer srv.Shutdown(ctx) or shuts down the DB pool before draining requests.</description>
        <reason>Require an audit checklist. Graceful shutdown must close DB, drain queues, cancel contexts in the right order.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents drop graceful shutdown for worker binaries entirely.</description>
        <reason>Require a select { case &lt;-quit: case &lt;-ctx.Done(): } pattern in every long-running goroutine.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs use package-level var DB *sql.DB; this works for tutorials and breaks for tests.</description>
        <reason>Insist on constructor injection. Global state prevents parallel test execution and mocking.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents propose cyclic imports (handler → service → handler) when extracting interfaces.</description>
        <reason>Require a dependency graph review before commit. Cyclic imports reveal design flaws.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generated getEnvInt and similar helpers silently return defaults on parse error.</description>
        <reason>Require an explicit error-on-malformed mode. A missing PORT should fail startup, not default silently.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>An agent migrating from flat layout often rewrites import paths globally and breaks vendored modules.</description>
        <reason>Require a go build ./... proof and a check for replace directives in go.mod.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Any move into internal/ from a previously exported path is a public-API break.</description>
        <reason>Agents underestimate this. Require a human checkpoint before breaking public APIs.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents emit Dockerfile without USER nobody and without distroless base.</description>
        <reason>Review for prod-readiness. No binaries should run as root.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>Essential CLI tools for Go project development:</p>
      <list>
        <item>go mod: Module management — stdlib</item>
        <item>golangci-lint: Aggregator linter — https://golangci-lint.run</item>
        <item>staticcheck: Deeper static analysis — https://staticcheck.dev</item>
        <item>govulncheck: CVE scan for deps — https://go.dev/blog/vuln</item>
        <item>gotestsum: Pretty test runner — https://github.com/gotestyourself/gotestsum</item>
        <item>air: Live reload during dev — https://github.com/cosmtrek/air</item>
        <item>mockery / gomock: Generate mocks for repository interfaces</item>
        <item>wire: Compile-time DI when manual wiring grows — https://github.com/google/wire</item>
        <item>go-licenses: License compliance check — https://github.com/google/go-licenses</item>
        <item>koanf / viper / envconfig: Typed config loaders</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/new-resource.sh" purpose="Shell script to scaffold handler/service/repository/model for a new resource."/>
      <template path="templates/Makefile" purpose="Standard Makefile with build, run, test, lint, docker targets."/>
      <template path="templates/Dockerfile" purpose="Multi-stage distroless Dockerfile for Go services."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://github.com/golang-standards/project-layout"/>
      <link href="https://go.dev/doc/effective_go"/>
      <link href="https://go.dev/ref/mod"/>
      <link href="https://github.com/uber-go/guide"/>
      <link href="https://dave.cheney.net/practical-go/presentations/qcon-china.html"/>
      <link href="https://google.github.io/styleguide/go/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
